Anually

3rd Saturday

of June

June 17th 2017

&amp;nbsp;


It&amp;#39;s the Fiddletown Community Center&amp;#39;s Annual Fiddletown Flea!&amp;nbsp; This is a giant community yard sale held in the park on the main street in Fiddletown and, many private residences in the surrounding area. Maps will be available to guide attendees to the multiple venues. Food and beverages will be available for purchase.&amp;nbsp; Vendors welcome. For directions or any other questions please call (209)296-0918.


&amp;nbsp;

The Fiddletown Community Center

14445 Fiddletown Road


P. O. Box 236

Fiddletown, CA&amp;nbsp; 95629


(209) 245-6042

&amp;nbsp;

www.fiddletownca.org

&amp;nbsp;

www.fiddletown.info


&amp;nbsp;



February 2016

It is true that one man&amp;rsquo;s trash can be another man&amp;rsquo;s treasure, especially at this year&amp;rsquo;s Fiddletown Flea. This annual flea market boasts several locations in and around Fiddletown, plus a caf&amp;eacute; in the Fiddletown Community Center with food, drinks and souvenirs.


This year&amp;rsquo;s event will have vendors in the park, many residential locations and, vendors in the community hall as well. Also, this year part of the community hall will be turned into a caf&amp;eacute; with food, beverages and souvenirs including Fiddletown T-shirts, hats, postcards and bumper stickers available for purchase. 

This event is an opportunity for all the local organizations, The Fiddletown Community Center, The Fiddletown Preservation Society, The Moose Lodge, Fiddletown Community Church and the residents to join together, enjoy the fun and do a little fundraising says Florence Chilton, founder of the Flea. Out of town visitors will enjoy roaming the hills around Fiddletown, visiting with the sellers, finding unusual items and getting a peek into a lifestyle different from their own. It&amp;rsquo;s also an opportunity to view some really special gardens. Always hot on the item list are antiques. You never know what someone may find in their barn that they no longer have a use for. Cast iron cookware, tools and lots of miscellaneous. 

This ninth annual event was started by Chilton after moving to Fiddletown in 2001. While unpacking boxes, Chilton realized she had too much stuff. She thought about having a yard sale, but quickly remembered how far out of town they now were and that they would probably not get much traffic, she said. After talking with several of her neighbors, she found that they had the same complaint. When she suggested that they hold a sale at the local park, one neighbor commented that they had too much stuff to haul to the park. That is when Chilton came up with the idea for the Fiddletown Flea, a combination event for those that wanted to be at the park and those who wanted to participate at home. The Fiddletown Community Center sent out applications with a great response.&amp;nbsp; &amp;ldquo;Our first year we had seven vendors in the park and six remote locations,&amp;rdquo; Chilton said. &amp;ldquo;It turned into a giant scavenger hunt.&amp;nbsp; Several of the remote locations were old family farms that had just incredible stuff collected for generations. Also, several of the locations had plants for sale for really good prices.&amp;quot; Because locations varied from the park to around town, Chilton tries to keep the number of remote locations limited to 12 to 14 so all are easily visited.&amp;nbsp; 

The event has always been well attended. Cost for a booth at the park or a listing on the map is $20. Anyone with questions may call Chilton at 209-296-0918. Maps with detailed directions to the all locations will be handed out at the park and several of the homes. Chilton&amp;rsquo;s favorite part of the event &amp;ldquo;is the shopping of course,&amp;rdquo; she said. &amp;ldquo;I do have a slight advantage as I go out to each of the sites the day before to place signage, I get a sneak preview.&amp;quot; Early Saturday morning I again visit each site to make sure everyone is ready &amp;ndash; that is when the bartering begins and the real fun starts.&amp;rdquo; After the shopping is done and lunch is over, a quick trip over the hill is in order. That is where the Shanendoah Valley is located. With many beautiful wineries serving award winning wines, it is a lovely way to end a day in the Amador foothills. -&amp;nbsp; FleaMarkets.in/Fiddletown/California





&amp;nbsp;

The Fiddletown Community Center

14445 Fiddletown Road


P. O. Box 236

Fiddletown, CA&amp;nbsp; 95629


(209) 245-6042

&amp;nbsp;

www.fiddletownca.org

&amp;nbsp;

www.fiddletown.info

